<section xml:id="TI3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" tbil-slides="build">
  <title>Integration of trigonometry (TI3)</title>
    <objectives>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <xi:include href="outcomes/03.ptx"/>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>
    
    <activity xml:id="activity-TI3oddOdd">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Consider <m>\displaystyle\int \sin(x)\cos(x) \, dx</m>.  Which strategy would you choose to evaluate this integral?
                    <ol label="A">
                        <li>The method of substitution</li>
                        <li>Integration by parts</li>
                        <li>Other (specify your strategy)</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
    </activity>
    <activity xml:id="activity-TI3evenOdd">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Consider <m>\displaystyle\int \sin^2(x)\cos(x) \, dx</m>.  Which strategy would you choose to evaluate this integral?
                    <ol label="A">
                        <li>The method of substitution</li>
                        <li>Integration by parts</li>
                        <li>Other (specify your strategy)</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
    </activity>
    
    <activity xml:id="activity-TI3evenEven">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Consider <m>\displaystyle\int \sin^2(x)\cos^2(x) \, dx</m>.  Which strategy would you choose to evaluate this integral?
                    <ol label="A">
                        <li>The method of substitution</li>
                        <li>Integration by parts</li>
                        <li>Other (specify your strategy)</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
    </activity>
    
    
    <activity xml:id="activity-TI3evenEvenRedux">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let's consider <m>\displaystyle\int \sin^2(x)\cos^2(x) \, dx</m> again.
                    <ol label="A">
                        <li>Use the fact that <m>\cos^2(\theta)=\displaystyle\frac{1+cos(2\theta)}{2}</m> and <m>\sin^2(\theta)=\displaystyle\frac{1-cos(2\theta)}{2}</m> to rewrite the integrand using the above identities to an integral involving <m>\cos^2(2x)</m>. </li>
                        <li>Use the above identities to rewrite this new integrand as one involving <m>\cos(4x)</m>. </li>
                        <li>Evaluate the integral.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
    </activity>
    
    
    <activity xml:id="activity-TI3evenOddGeneral">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Consider <m>\displaystyle\int \sin^m(x)\cos^n(x) \, dx</m>, where <m>m</m> is even and <m>n</m> is odd.  Which strategy would you choose to evaluate this integral?
                    <ol label="A">
                        <li>Rewrite sine in terms of cosine by using a double-angle/half-angle identity.</li>
                        <li>Rewrite cosine in terms of sine by using a double-angle/half-angle identity.</li>
                        <li>Rewrite cosine in terms of sine by using a pythagorean identity.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
    </activity>
    
    
    <activity xml:id="activity-TI3oddOddGeneral">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Consider <m>\displaystyle\int \sin^m(x)\cos^n(x) \, dx</m>, where <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are both odd and <m>m\geq n</m>.  Which strategy would you choose to evaluate this integral?
                    <ol label="A">
                        <li>Rewrite sine in terms of cosine by using a pythagorean identity.</li>
                        <li>Rewrite cosine in terms of sine by using a double-angle/half-angle identity.</li>
                        <li>Rewrite cosine in terms of sine by using a pythagorean identity.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
    </activity>
    
    
    
    
    
    
    <activity xml:id="activity-TI3evenEvenGeneral">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Consider <m>\displaystyle\int \sin^m(x)\cos^n(x) \, dx</m>, where <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are both even and <m>m\geq n</m>.  Which strategy would you choose to evaluate this integral?
                    <ol label="A">
                        <li>Rewrite sine in terms of cosine by using a pythagorean identity.</li>
                        <li>Rewrite cosine in terms of sine by using a pythagorean identity.</li>
                        <li>Rewrite everything in terms of cosine by using a double-angle/half-angle identity.</li>                        
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
    </activity>
    
    
    
    <activity xml:id="activity-TI3evenEvenFluency">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Consider <m>\displaystyle\int \sin^4(x)\cos^4(x) \, dx</m>.  Which would be the most useful way to rewrite the integral?
                    <ol label="A">
                        <li><m>\displaystyle\int (1-\cos^2(x))^2\cos^4(x) \, dx</m></li>
                        <li><m>\displaystyle\int \sin^4(x)(1-\sin^2(x))^2 \, dx</m></li>
                        <li><m>\displaystyle\int \left(\frac{1-\cos(2x)}{2}\right)^2\left(\frac{1+\cos(2x)}{2}\right)^2 \, dx</m></li>                        
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
    </activity>
    
    
    <activity xml:id="activity-TI3oddOddFluency">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Consider <m>\displaystyle\int \sin^3(x)\cos^5(x) \, dx</m>.  Which would be the most useful way to rewrite the integral?
                    <ol label="A">
                        <li><m>\displaystyle\int (1-\cos^2(x))\sin(x)\cos^5(x) \, dx</m></li>
                        <li><m>\displaystyle\int \sin^3(x)\left(\frac{1+\cos(2x)}{2}\right)^2\cos(x) \, dx</m></li>
                        <li><m>\displaystyle\int \sin^3(x)(1-\sin^2(x))^2\cos(x) \, dx</m></li>                        
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
    </activity>
    
    
    
    <remark>
        <statement>
            <p>
We might also use some other trigonometric identities to manipulate our integrands, listed in
<xref ref="trig-table"/>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </remark>
    
    
    
    
    <activity xml:id="activity-TI3productSumFlex">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Consider <m>\displaystyle\int \sin(\theta)\sin(3\theta) \, d\theta</m>.
                    <ol label="A">
                        <li>Find an identity from the table above which could be used to transform our integrand.</li>
                        <li>Rewrite the integrand using the selected identity.</li>
                        <li>Evaluate the integral.</li>                        
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
    </activity>
    
    
    
    
